SIMPLE: whore
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Whore
<hw>Whore</hw> <pr>(h⟦omac⟧r)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>hore</ets>, AS. <ets>h⟦omac⟧re</ets>; akin to D. <ets>hoer</ets>,
<ets>hoere</ets>, G. <ets>hure</ets>, OHG. <ets>huora</ets>,
<ets>huorra</ets>, Icel. <ets>h⟦omac⟧ra</ets>, Dan. <ets>hore</ets>, Sw.
<ets>hora</ets>, Goth. <ets>h⟦omac⟧rs</ets> an adulterer, AS.
<ets>h⟦omac⟧r</ets> adultery, OHG. <ets>huor</ets>, and probably to L.
<ets>carus</ets> dear. Cf. <er>Charity</er>.]</ety> <def>A woman who
practices unlawful sexual commerce with men, especially one who
prostitutes her body for hire; a prostitute; a harlot.</def>
<rj><au>Wyclif.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Harlot; courtesan; prostitute;
strumpet.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Whore</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Whore
<hw>Whore</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Whored</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Whoring</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. Icel. <ets>h<?/ra</ets>. See
<er>Whore</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To have unlawful sexual intercourse; to practice
lewdness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Script.)</fld> <def>To worship false and impure
gods.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Whore</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Whore
<hw>Whore</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To corrupt by lewd intercourse; to
make a whore of; to debauch.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Congreve.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Whoredom</ent>⟦br⟧
